<TITLE> Dolphin exhibition draws crowds </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 9 (bdnews24.com) - The first ever Whale and Dolphin Exhibition drew large numbers of nature lovers in Dhaka as it opened Thursday. Children especially crowded Bangladesh Shishu Academy from morning to visit the exhibition or 'Shushuk Mela'. The interactive exhibition and film show, organised by Bangladesh Cetacean Diversity Project with sponsorship from the US Wildlife Conservation Society, will remain open from 9.30am to 8.30pm every day until Oct 12. Entrance is free. BCDP works to conserve diversity and abundance of whales, dolphins and porpoises in Bangladesh in cooperation with local communities and institutions. The exhibition aims at introducing Bangladesh's cetaceans and ongoing conservation efforts to the public. Through photographs, film shows, games, and models the organisers of this four-day event hope to create a sense of pride and to foster support for the conservation of these unique aquatic animals, said the organisers of the exhibition. Parallel to the exhibition a seminar series is being held on Saturday focusing on the research and conservation efforts carried out so far in Bangladesh. A proposed "Protected Area Network for Cetacean Diversity" will be presented to the public, academic institutions, policy makers and conservation organisations. Whales, dolphins and porpoises are among the largest and most intelligent of mammals, found in all the oceans of the globe. At present there are more than 80 species of whales, dolphins and porpoises in the world. The Blue Whale is the biggest animal on earth, at up to 100 metres long. Shushuk or the Gangetic Dolphin is a species found in big rivers of Bangladesh. bdnews
